  1189	 The notation used is the conventional one. In the first term of (61),
  1190	the sum is over $S$ electrons and $\delta(r_m)$, the Dirac delta
  1191	function which vanishes unless the electron is at the nucleus; the
  1192	second sum in $\mathcal{H}^{(2)}$ is over electrons other than $S$
  1193	electrons. In (62), $x_i$ and $x_k$ are the Cartesian coordinates of the
  1194	nuclear charge of the nucleus of interest, $Q_{ik}$ is an operator,
  1195	$\phi$ is the electrostatic potential, and $Q$ is the quadrupole moment
  1196	of the nucleus. $\mathcal{H}^{(4)}$ is obtained if it is assumed the
  1197	$m$th electron is in the combined external and nuclear field
  1198	$H_m=H+\mu g \mathrm{grad}(I\cdot\nabla 1/r_m)$, and the vector
  1199	potential is taken to be
  1200	$A_m=\frac{1}{2}H\times r_m - \mu g I \times \nabla(1/r_m)$. The $r_m$
  1201	is the position vector of the $m$th electron relative to the nucleus to
  1202	which it is bound.
  1203	
  1204	Unlike the calculation of the electronic gyromagnetic effects, we have
