  1080	a rotation $\omega_E$ of the vessel.
  1081	### Polarization of Nuclear Spins in a Crystal
  1082	Since most nuclei, like electrons, posses both a spin angular momentum
  1083	and a parallel magnetic moment in their ground state, and since angular
  1084	momentum can be exchanged between nuclear spins and lattice motion, we
  1085	expect at least in principle that polarization of nuclei by the rotation
  1086	of a macroscopic sample, the nuclear analog of the Barnett effect, is
  1087	possible. The polarization of nuclei by a magnetic field requires a
  1088	means for balancing the angular momentum acquired by the nuclei. One
  1089	such means is the rotation of the whole lattice. This occurrence is the
  1090	nuclear analog of the Einstein-deHaas effect. We discuss in the
  1091	following the polarization of nuclei due to the simultaneous action of
  1092	an external field and a rotation, thus including both effects. The
  1093	coupling of the nuclear spins with the crystal environment is treated as
  1094	a perturbation, whereas the action of the field and the rotation on the
  1095	uncoupled nucleus are treated exactly. In evaluating the polarization of
  1096	the nuclear spins, the simplifying assumption is made that in the
  1097	stationary crystal the nuclei have no orbital angular momentum.
  1098	
  1099	Consider a single-spin operator $I$ expressed in units of $\hbar$ with
